Hello Bhaskar Chowdhury,

I have two quick tips for you today which I found useful last
week.

#1 tip

You should already know that if you run:

vim +2806 big_file.txt

you'll open up this file with cursor positioned on line 2806.

What if you know that you'll be editing a file at the end of it,
but you have no idea how many lines is has? Or it might be a very
big file.

Well, if you don't specify a number after +, Vim will do exactly
that.

vim + big_file.txt

will open big_file.txt with cursor positioned at the last line of
the file.

#2 tip

Did you know you can navigate the cursor to a specific column of
the current line using | character?

For example, hitting 28| in Normal mode will take your cursor to
the 28th column of the current line. If your number exceeds the
number of columns on the line, your cursor will end up on the
last column.

That's all for today Bhaskar Chowdhury.
I wish you a great week! :)

Cheers,
Jovica

